WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.320 --> 00:00:06.040
&gt;&gt;Reto: Good afternoon and welcome again to
the Friday review of apps.

00:00:06.040 --> 00:00:07.240
My name is Reto Meier.

00:00:07.240 --> 00:00:09.480
And joining me in the studio I have with me
Trevor Jones.

00:00:09.480 --> 00:00:10.480
&gt;&gt;Trevor: Hi there everyone.

00:00:10.480 --> 00:00:15.669
&gt;&gt;Reto: And via the miracle of modern technology
joining us from his new abode in New York

00:00:15.669 --> 00:00:17.980
City, we have Romain Yurik.

00:00:17.980 --> 00:00:19.599
&gt;&gt;Romain: Hello everyone.

00:00:19.599 --> 00:00:21.210
&gt;&gt;Reto: Hey Romain.

00:00:21.210 --> 00:00:24.449
Thank you for joining us in your flickery
self.

00:00:24.449 --> 00:00:28.550
So we're going to take a look at a few apps
today.

00:00:28.550 --> 00:00:33.670
And while Ian tries to figure out what the
flickering is about.

00:00:33.670 --> 00:00:36.010
We may start off by having a look at Samo
Color.

00:00:36.010 --> 00:00:37.800
So we're also going to look at GPS.

00:00:37.800 --> 00:00:39.690
Test a couple of notes apps.

00:00:39.690 --> 00:00:41.930
And some exercise apps as well . Run Double.

00:00:41.930 --> 00:00:45.550
So we've got quite an interesting and eclectic
collection for you today.

00:00:45.550 --> 00:00:46.930
So shall we get started.

00:00:46.930 --> 00:00:48.309
&gt;&gt;Trevor: Sure, Let's, go ahead.

00:00:48.309 --> 00:00:54.300
&gt;&gt;Reto: Let's have a look at Samo Color.

00:00:54.300 --> 00:00:58.719
So we're going to fire this up on the phone
over here.

00:00:58.719 --> 00:01:02.730
So, I'll wait 'til Ian gets a chance.

00:01:02.730 --> 00:01:03.730
Excellent.

00:01:03.730 --> 00:01:05.160
Oops, I had that space.

00:01:05.160 --> 00:01:06.160
Alright.

00:01:06.160 --> 00:01:07.160
Perfect.

00:01:07.160 --> 00:01:08.160
So here we go.

00:01:08.160 --> 00:01:09.460
So Samo Color by Code Carpet.

00:01:09.460 --> 00:01:11.009
Tap three times to buy.

00:01:11.009 --> 00:01:13.330
I wonder what my alternatives are.

00:01:13.330 --> 00:01:15.870
So I can see an arrow here so I'm gonna slide
across.

00:01:15.870 --> 00:01:19.250
And I can see a number of different options
here.

00:01:19.250 --> 00:01:20.430
Not entirely sure what they are.

00:01:20.430 --> 00:01:21.430
OK.

00:01:21.430 --> 00:01:22.430
So they're locked.

00:01:22.430 --> 00:01:23.430
Alright.

00:01:23.430 --> 00:01:24.430
So we'll go here and click.

00:01:24.430 --> 00:01:25.430
Oh, OK.

00:01:25.430 --> 00:01:26.430
Interesting.

00:01:26.430 --> 00:01:31.700
So this is, in case it wasn't obvious, this
is an app which is targeted towards children.

00:01:31.700 --> 00:01:35.479
&gt;&gt;Trevor: Hence the tap three times to buy.

00:01:35.479 --> 00:01:36.479
&gt;&gt;Reto: [laughs] Indeed.

00:01:36.479 --> 00:01:37.479
Mostly children who can't read.

00:01:37.479 --> 00:01:38.479
&gt;&gt;Trevor: Actually, it's not a bad idea.

00:01:38.479 --> 00:01:40.950
'Cause a lot of times people, you know we
hear from people who write apps or directed

00:01:40.950 --> 00:01:46.280
towards apps who are targeted towards children
is that there's these "buy" buttons and children

00:01:46.280 --> 00:01:48.200
just go and hit on them accidentally.

00:01:48.200 --> 00:01:52.450
So I like that you have, like, kids are just
going to go and mash on the screen.

00:01:52.450 --> 00:01:55.880
So anything to go and prevent them from accidentally
buying is probably a good thing.

00:01:55.880 --> 00:01:56.880
&gt;&gt;Reto: Probably a good thing.

00:01:56.880 --> 00:01:57.880
Absolutely.

00:01:57.880 --> 00:02:00.369
Although I wonder, I wonder if you wanna go
a step further and actually hide that behind

00:02:00.369 --> 00:02:02.539
a menu option or something like that.

00:02:02.539 --> 00:02:03.539
&gt;&gt;Trevor: Yeah.

00:02:03.539 --> 00:02:05.860
It's probably a good idea to actually go all
the way to turn on the pin lock and mark it.

00:02:05.860 --> 00:02:06.860
But.

00:02:06.860 --> 00:02:07.860
&gt;&gt;Reto: Yeah.

00:02:07.860 --> 00:02:08.860
That's a very good point.

00:02:08.860 --> 00:02:10.410
But still it's a good point you make.

00:02:10.410 --> 00:02:16.660
So the idea here is that you can color in
the little guy on screen.

00:02:16.660 --> 00:02:18.430
Using the colors at our disposal.

00:02:18.430 --> 00:02:20.310
Let's see, give him green ears.

00:02:20.310 --> 00:02:21.310
Blue.

00:02:21.310 --> 00:02:22.510
&gt;&gt;Trevor: There are actually more colors.

00:02:22.510 --> 00:02:24.080
&gt;&gt;Reto: There are more colors?

00:02:24.080 --> 00:02:25.080
Oh, look at that.

00:02:25.080 --> 00:02:26.080
I can swipe to get more colors.

00:02:26.080 --> 00:02:27.080
&gt;&gt;Trevor: Took me a moment to figure that
out.

00:02:27.080 --> 00:02:28.080
&gt;&gt;Reto: Interesting.

00:02:28.080 --> 00:02:30.280
&gt;&gt;Trevor: I mean it is a little widget down
there to go and show you more pages.

00:02:30.280 --> 00:02:31.280
&gt;&gt;Reto: That's true.

00:02:31.280 --> 00:02:34.150
&gt;&gt;Trevor: But amongst all the noise of all
the colors, it's actually really easy to miss.

00:02:34.150 --> 00:02:39.710
&gt;&gt;Reto: It didn't occur to me that the pager
was resp-- was talking about the colors themselves.

00:02:39.710 --> 00:02:41.030
That's interesting.

00:02:41.030 --> 00:02:45.490
So, OK, so what I would say is, in a particular
for something just color in here.

00:02:45.490 --> 00:02:46.600
&gt;&gt;Trevor: There's also a menu too, by the
way.

00:02:46.600 --> 00:02:47.720
&gt;&gt;Reto: I saw it does have a menu.

00:02:47.720 --> 00:02:48.720
&gt;&gt;Trevor: No, not that menu.

00:02:48.720 --> 00:02:49.720
&gt;&gt;Reto: Ah.

00:02:49.720 --> 00:02:52.000
&gt;&gt;Trevor: See the little black thing with
eyes.

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:53.280
&gt;&gt;Reto: Ooooh.

00:02:53.280 --> 00:02:54.280
It's a menu.

00:02:54.280 --> 00:02:55.280
That's interesting.

00:02:55.280 --> 00:02:56.280
So two points here.

00:02:56.280 --> 00:02:58.470
First is, let me just, scroll up slightly.

00:02:58.470 --> 00:02:59.801
Menu button of shame.

00:02:59.801 --> 00:03:01.150
Because it's there but doesn't do anything.

00:03:01.150 --> 00:03:04.221
&gt;&gt;Trevor: Especially, especially because there
isn't anything, there's really no reason to

00:03:04.221 --> 00:03:05.221
have that.

00:03:05.221 --> 00:03:06.221
&gt;&gt;Reto: Exactly.

00:03:06.221 --> 00:03:09.790
So that's the big hate we have for the menu
button being there, is if it actually doesn't

00:03:09.790 --> 00:03:10.790
do anything.

00:03:10.790 --> 00:03:12.900
&gt;&gt;Trevor: Even if it still does something,
you shouldn't have it anymore.

00:03:12.900 --> 00:03:13.900
&gt;&gt;Reto: That's true.

00:03:13.900 --> 00:03:14.900
That's true.

00:03:14.900 --> 00:03:16.470
&gt;&gt;Trevor: There is no excuse for having a
menu button at this point.

00:03:16.470 --> 00:03:19.730
&gt;&gt;Reto: Yeah, I think we've got, I think we've
moved on far enough now.

00:03:19.730 --> 00:03:20.730
With Jellybean coming out.

00:03:20.730 --> 00:03:23.350
&gt;&gt;Trevor: With Jellybean now, yes, now our
second release where the menu button.

00:03:23.350 --> 00:03:24.350
Well, if you can't.

00:03:24.350 --> 00:03:25.350
There you go.

00:03:25.350 --> 00:03:26.610
Third release where the menu button is just
deprecated.

00:03:26.610 --> 00:03:29.940
So yeah, at this point we really shouldn't
be seeing that anymore.

00:03:29.940 --> 00:03:33.380
&gt;&gt;Reto: Exactly, so that would be step one
is remove that menu button.

00:03:33.380 --> 00:03:35.940
Now, having the little eyes, that's interesting.

00:03:35.940 --> 00:03:38.700
So, now, I see, you actually drag it.

00:03:38.700 --> 00:03:39.960
&gt;&gt;Trevor: You can click as well.

00:03:39.960 --> 00:03:44.210
&gt;&gt;Reto: Click-tug doesn't seem to be working
100 percent of the time.

00:03:44.210 --> 00:03:45.210
So that's a bit fade back.

00:03:45.210 --> 00:03:46.210
But.

00:03:46.210 --> 00:03:47.210
&gt;&gt;Trevor: Yes.

00:03:47.210 --> 00:03:48.210
&gt;&gt;Reto: It also works.

00:03:48.210 --> 00:03:49.210
The dragging is quite nice.

00:03:49.210 --> 00:03:50.210
&gt;&gt;Trevor: Yeah.

00:03:50.210 --> 00:03:51.210
The other thing that confused me to.

00:03:51.210 --> 00:03:52.210
Now, that back button, what would, would you
think that's "back"?

00:03:52.210 --> 00:03:54.710
&gt;&gt;Reto: Ah, that's a good question.

00:03:54.710 --> 00:03:55.960
It's just above the other back button.

00:03:55.960 --> 00:03:57.020
I would probably think undo.

00:03:57.020 --> 00:03:58.020
&gt;&gt;Trevor: It is undo.

00:03:58.020 --> 00:03:59.020
&gt;&gt;Reto: Yeah.

00:03:59.020 --> 00:04:00.020
&gt;&gt;Trevor: But it took me a while.

00:04:00.020 --> 00:04:01.120
I was like, what's gonna happen if I push
this button?

00:04:01.120 --> 00:04:02.120
&gt;&gt;Reto: Yeah, definitely.

00:04:02.120 --> 00:04:05.040
Anything which looks like a back button I
think you're kind of taking your usability

00:04:05.040 --> 00:04:06.530
into your own hands here.

00:04:06.530 --> 00:04:09.050
'Cause you suddenly go, oooh, is this gonna
exit?

00:04:09.050 --> 00:04:10.620
Now clearly kids aren't gonna think that.

00:04:10.620 --> 00:04:11.990
They're probably also not gonna think "undo."

00:04:11.990 --> 00:04:14.700
&gt;&gt;Trevor: Well, they might think the regular
back button thing is "undo".

00:04:14.700 --> 00:04:15.700
&gt;&gt;Reto: Oh.

00:04:15.700 --> 00:04:16.700
That's a good point.

00:04:16.700 --> 00:04:19.650
Particularly once you've made it ambiguous
here that maybe "back" means "undo".

00:04:19.650 --> 00:04:22.030
You probably wanna simplify that.

00:04:22.030 --> 00:04:24.350
So I don't think this is discoverable at all.

00:04:24.350 --> 00:04:26.780
It would never have occurred to me to press
the googly eyes.

00:04:26.780 --> 00:04:31.070
Now, in fairness a six year old probably would
think to hit pretty much everything on the

00:04:31.070 --> 00:04:32.070
screen.

00:04:32.070 --> 00:04:33.070
So that would help.

00:04:33.070 --> 00:04:34.070
But, there's an awful lot--

00:04:34.070 --> 00:04:37.100
&gt;&gt;Trevor: let me ask if there's multi level
undo.

00:04:37.100 --> 00:04:39.320
But it's a children's app, so we'll give them
a pass on that.

00:04:39.320 --> 00:04:40.320
&gt;&gt;Reto: Yeah.

00:04:40.320 --> 00:04:41.320
Exactly.

00:04:41.320 --> 00:04:42.320
That would be nice.

00:04:42.320 --> 00:04:45.721
And particularly like, so once you hit undo
having that stay onscreen so that you can

00:04:45.721 --> 00:04:47.850
do multilevel undo would be nice.

00:04:47.850 --> 00:04:55.260
But maybe, maybe have these as, as an action
bar along the top might be interesting.

00:04:55.260 --> 00:04:56.900
I guess you wanna keep the screen clutter
down.

00:04:56.900 --> 00:04:59.100
You don't want to have people accidentally
pressing buttons.

00:04:59.100 --> 00:05:01.590
So having it hidden in a way is useful, but.

00:05:01.590 --> 00:05:05.190
&gt;&gt;Trevor: Again, there is the argument that
kids are going to mash everything on the screen.

00:05:05.190 --> 00:05:07.160
So I can sort of see the argument for hiding
it.

00:05:07.160 --> 00:05:09.260
But I think the discoverability could really
be improved.

00:05:09.260 --> 00:05:10.260
&gt;&gt;Reto: Yeah.

00:05:10.260 --> 00:05:11.260
What do you think Romain?

00:05:11.260 --> 00:05:16.000
Do you have a, from a usability perspective,
an idea here of how you can maybe make this

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:17.070
more or less obvious?

00:05:17.070 --> 00:05:24.760
&gt;&gt;Romain: Yeah, I mean, I think the first
thing is that, asking kids to discover slidy

00:05:24.760 --> 00:05:28.530
things, like sliding drawers, that's, I think
that's asking a little too much.

00:05:28.530 --> 00:05:34.080
You know in general we recommend using gestures
to uncover things.

00:05:34.080 --> 00:05:36.710
Sliding drawers, I personally am kind of against.

00:05:36.710 --> 00:05:39.810
But you know, using gestures is normally ok.

00:05:39.810 --> 00:05:42.720
Like paging between screens and things like
that.

00:05:42.720 --> 00:05:48.840
But for kids, you know kids kind of, they
understand you know, simple gestures.

00:05:48.840 --> 00:05:49.840
Like sliding.

00:05:49.840 --> 00:05:52.810
But it has to be really really really obvious.

00:05:52.810 --> 00:05:54.140
And I don't think it's obvious in this case.

00:05:54.140 --> 00:05:58.900
What I'd probably do instead is really just
put it on screen.

00:05:58.900 --> 00:06:00.630
And for thinks like "back".

00:06:00.630 --> 00:06:06.840
For things like navigating to other pieces
of art, it's actually like right now, once

00:06:06.840 --> 00:06:12.420
you're in a drawing, there's no real way to
get to other drawings.

00:06:12.420 --> 00:06:14.450
So for that you may wanna use gestures.

00:06:14.450 --> 00:06:19.910
Like maybe slide left to kind of go back to
the top level screen.

00:06:19.910 --> 00:06:24.090
But you know, sliding up a thing to reveal
actions or even at the very bottom something

00:06:24.090 --> 00:06:28.290
as simple as using a view pager to slide between
different colors.

00:06:28.290 --> 00:06:30.300
Even that may be a little too unobvious.

00:06:30.300 --> 00:06:33.170
So in that case maybe just have left and right
buttons.

00:06:33.170 --> 00:06:34.170
&gt;&gt;Trevor: Right.

00:06:34.170 --> 00:06:35.170
&gt;&gt;Romain: [inaudible]

00:06:35.170 --> 00:06:37.350
&gt;&gt;Trevor: Well there's already two people
that didn't notice you could slide the colors.

00:06:37.350 --> 00:06:38.350
So.

00:06:38.350 --> 00:06:39.350
&gt;&gt;Reto: Yeah.

00:06:39.350 --> 00:06:41.100
[laughs] 'Cause that's, actually that gesture
you described is what I assumed the pager

00:06:41.100 --> 00:06:42.100
was for.

00:06:42.100 --> 00:06:45.380
If I started swiping left or right it would
take me to a different pictures.

00:06:45.380 --> 00:06:46.380
&gt;&gt;Trevor: Yeah.

00:06:46.380 --> 00:06:49.050
&gt;&gt;Reto: That's why the visual cue wasn't obvious
to me that it was [inaudible]

00:06:49.050 --> 00:06:53.139
&gt;&gt;Romain: I think, just, like in generally
when dealing with kids apps you wanna put

00:06:53.139 --> 00:06:58.200
more stuff in a fun, like friendly, like picture
form onscreen.

00:06:58.200 --> 00:07:01.120
Rather than rely on gestures too much.

00:07:01.120 --> 00:07:02.810
So I think in this case kids may get confused.

00:07:02.810 --> 00:07:05.040
Like "Oh, how do I get back to whatever."

00:07:05.040 --> 00:07:07.200
And obviously grownups will know that oh,
you press the back button.

00:07:07.200 --> 00:07:08.630
It's the android back button.

00:07:08.630 --> 00:07:11.970
But kids aren't as, they're not as used to
using the smart phones.

00:07:11.970 --> 00:07:12.970
&gt;&gt;Trevor: Hm.

00:07:12.970 --> 00:07:16.520
&gt;&gt;Romain: So don't assume that's standard,
kind of android patterns apply.

00:07:16.520 --> 00:07:20.460
&gt;&gt;Reto: Yeah, I think that's particularly
through because while it's good that they

00:07:20.460 --> 00:07:23.400
put this consistent approach to using the
pager.

00:07:23.400 --> 00:07:28.010
And you know I'm quite a fan of having this
indicator to show you what page you're on.

00:07:28.010 --> 00:07:31.370
They use it to me, sort of different things
on different pages.

00:07:31.370 --> 00:07:34.780
Oops, managed to exit.

00:07:34.780 --> 00:07:36.860
Oh if you, that's another tip.

00:07:36.860 --> 00:07:39.360
If I exit from a particular drawing.

00:07:39.360 --> 00:07:45.210
So if I exit from here when hitting back,
when I reload the app I should go back to

00:07:45.210 --> 00:07:46.639
that, to the same place I was.

00:07:46.639 --> 00:07:50.740
'cause the chances of someone, particularly
a kid, hitting back and being like "Oh, I've

00:07:50.740 --> 00:07:51.740
lost everything."

00:07:51.740 --> 00:07:52.740
Is high.

00:07:52.740 --> 00:07:56.110
But yeah, so they've used it up here to page
between pictures and once you go in they use

00:07:56.110 --> 00:07:59.139
it to page between colors.

00:07:59.139 --> 00:08:01.990
Which I think is somewhat confusing.

00:08:01.990 --> 00:08:04.710
Particularly 'cause this isn't, is it a proper
pager?

00:08:04.710 --> 00:08:05.710
I guess it is.

00:08:05.710 --> 00:08:07.610
It's showing a set of different colors each
time.

00:08:07.610 --> 00:08:08.610
But yeah.

00:08:08.610 --> 00:08:12.090
Having that same visual metaphor meaning two
different things can be a little bit confusing.

00:08:12.090 --> 00:08:16.810
&gt;&gt;Romain: Yeah, what you may wanna do is,
when having lots of colors.

00:08:16.810 --> 00:08:19.030
In this case there's lots and lots of colors.

00:08:19.030 --> 00:08:20.030
There's a lot to choose from.

00:08:20.030 --> 00:08:25.370
You may wanna just have like, when you touch
the color it expands up to this larger palette

00:08:25.370 --> 00:08:27.510
to choose from.

00:08:27.510 --> 00:08:33.931
Or something even like, have them smaller
so that you, a kid can just drag their finger

00:08:33.931 --> 00:08:36.630
around like this massive color palette.

00:08:36.630 --> 00:08:40.229
The bottom shows them a preview of what color
their finger is on.

00:08:40.229 --> 00:08:42.450
Almost like a magnifying glass.

00:08:42.450 --> 00:08:45.240
That may make a little more sense than kind
of swiping left and right.

00:08:45.240 --> 00:08:46.240
&gt;&gt;Reto: Yeah.

00:08:46.240 --> 00:08:47.240
I think so too.

00:08:47.240 --> 00:08:51.900
Otherwise it's a, I really like the simplicity
of the app so it's, there's no ambiguity as

00:08:51.900 --> 00:08:52.900
to what you need to do.

00:08:52.900 --> 00:08:53.900
How it's gonna work.

00:08:53.900 --> 00:08:56.170
You get the immediate benefit.

00:08:56.170 --> 00:08:58.940
You hit the screen and things start to happen
which is really night.

00:08:58.940 --> 00:09:00.420
Pictures are nice.

00:09:00.420 --> 00:09:01.420
Cute too.

00:09:01.420 --> 00:09:04.200
Otherwise, yeah, I think its' quite a nice
app otherwise.

00:09:04.200 --> 00:09:07.120
&gt;&gt;Romain: There's one more thing I wanted
to add.

00:09:07.120 --> 00:09:08.120
&gt;&gt;Reto: Please.

00:09:08.120 --> 00:09:10.230
&gt;&gt;Romain: there's this one part of the app.

00:09:10.230 --> 00:09:14.890
I think it might be the page where the teacher
is standing and looking at a chalkboard.

00:09:14.890 --> 00:09:16.640
There's a bunch of different shapes there.

00:09:16.640 --> 00:09:19.210
So it's basically free form, you just draw
free form.

00:09:19.210 --> 00:09:20.540
&gt;&gt;Trevor: Oh really?

00:09:20.540 --> 00:09:22.400
&gt;&gt;Romain: And in that case what I would

00:09:22.400 --> 00:09:23.880
&gt;&gt;Reto: Ahhh.

00:09:23.880 --> 00:09:24.880
Nice.

00:09:24.880 --> 00:09:28.680
&gt;&gt;Romain: So, you should probably support
multitouch there.

00:09:28.680 --> 00:09:32.240
Kids love like placing all their fingers all
at once on the screen and dragging them.

00:09:32.240 --> 00:09:36.230
&gt;&gt;Trevor: Actually, I'd take that a step further
and try and detect pressure.

00:09:36.230 --> 00:09:37.230
&gt;&gt;Romain: Yes.

00:09:37.230 --> 00:09:42.860
So there's actually an open source app called
Markers that was recently released by Daniel

00:09:42.860 --> 00:09:44.800
Sandler who's on the Android team.

00:09:44.800 --> 00:09:50.090
